request_methods // HTTP method of the request (GET, POST, OPTIONS, etc.)
http_origin // value of the Origin header in the incoming request, which indicates the origin of the request (e.g., the domain from which the request is made)
valid_referes // This variable is used in conjunction with the "valid_referers" directive to check if the "Referer" header of incoming requests matches specified valid referrers. If a request's referrer does not match any of the defined valid referrers, the $invalid_referer variable will be set to 1 (true), indicating that the request has an invalid referrer. This can be used to implement access control based on the source of the request, allowing you to block requests that do not come from trusted sources.
$invalid_referer // This variable is set to 1 (true) when the "Referer" header of an incoming request does not match any of the specified valid referrers defined in the "valid_referers" directive. It indicates that the request has an invalid referrer, which can be used to implement access control by blocking requests that do not come from trusted sources.
$binary_remote_addr =provides the client's IP address in a compact binary format / used for efficient storage in shared memory zones
$upstream_cache_status / indicates whether the response was served from cache (HIT), generated by the backend (MISS), or bypassed (BYPASS)
$cookie_session; / checks for the presence of a session cookie, often used to determine if a user is logged in or has an active session
